n exploration of its parallels in other Buddhist cultures, its connection to the Vinaya, and its value as socio-historical source-material. The guidelines are witness to certain socio-economic changes, while also containing rules that aim to change the monastery in order to preserve it. Jansen argues that the monastic institutions' influence on society was maintained not merely due to prevailing power-relations, but also because of certain deep-rooted Buddhist beliefs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBuddhismxSocial aspectszChinazTibet Autonomous Region. 0aBuddhist monasticism and religious orderszChinazTibet Autonomous RegionvRules. 0aHistory (General). 0aHistory of Asia. 0aReligion (General). 7aHISTORY / Asia / Central Asia.2bisacsh  abca yig.  abuddhism.  abuddhist beliefs.  abuddhist cultural parallels.  abuddhist society.  achange the monastery.  aculture.  adeep rooted beliefs.  aeconomy.  aguidelines.  ainfluence on society.  alaw.  amonasteries.  amonastic buddhism.  amonastic guidelines.  apower relations.  apre 1950s.  apreserve the monastery.  asocio economic changes.  asocio historical source.  atibet.  atibetan society.  avinaya.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066767740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520969537zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520969537zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520969537/original  a978-3-11-066767-7 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018